     557                 :            : 
     558                 :            :    Usage of language-independent fields in a language-dependent manner:
     559                 :            : 
     560                 :            :    TYPE_ALIAS_SET
     561                 :            :      This field is used by TYPENAME_TYPEs, TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARMs, and so
     562                 :            :      forth as a substitute for the mark bits provided in `lang_type'.
     563                 :            :      At present, only the six low-order bits are used.
     564                 :            : 
     565                 :            :    TYPE_LANG_SLOT_1
     566                 :            :      For a FUNCTION_TYPE or METHOD_TYPE, this is TYPE_RAISES_EXCEPTIONS.
     567                 :            :      For a POINTER_TYPE (to a METHOD_TYPE), this is TYPE_PTRMEMFUNC_TYPE.
     568                 :            :      For an ENUMERAL_TYPE, BOUND_TEMPLATE_TEMPLATE_PARM_TYPE,
     569                 :            :      RECORD_TYPE or UNION_TYPE this is TYPE_TEMPLATE_INFO,
     570                 :            : 
     571                 :            :   BINFO_VIRTUALS
     572                 :            :      For a binfo, this is a TREE_LIST.  There is an entry for each
     573                 :            :      virtual function declared either in BINFO or its direct and
     574                 :            :      indirect primary bases.
     575                 :            : 
     576                 :            :      The BV_DELTA of each node gives the amount by which to adjust the
     577                 :            :      `this' pointer when calling the function.  If the method is an
     578                 :            :      overridden version of a base class method, then it is assumed
     579                 :            :      that, prior to adjustment, the this pointer points to an object
     580                 :            :      of the base class.
     581                 :            : 
     582                 :            :      The BV_VCALL_INDEX of each node, if non-NULL, gives the vtable
     583                 :            :      index of the vcall offset for this entry.
     584                 :            : 
     585                 :            :      The BV_FN is the declaration for the virtual function itself.
     586                 :            : 
     587                 :            :      If BV_LOST_PRIMARY is set, it means that this entry is for a lost
     588                 :            :      primary virtual base and can be left null in the vtable.
     589                 :            : 
     590                 :            :    BINFO_VTABLE
     591                 :            :      This is an expression with POINTER_TYPE that gives the value
     592                 :            :      to which the vptr should be initialized.  Use get_vtbl_decl_for_binfo
     593                 :            :      to extract the VAR_DECL for the complete vtable.
     594                 :            : 
     595                 :            :    DECL_VINDEX
     596                 :            :      This field is NULL for a non-virtual function.  For a virtual
     597                 :            :      function, it is eventually set to an INTEGER_CST indicating the
     598                 :            :      index in the vtable at which this function can be found.  When
     599                 :            :      a virtual function is declared, but before it is known what
     600                 :            :      function is overridden, this field is the error_mark_node.
     601                 :            : 
     602                 :            :      Temporarily, it may be set to a TREE_LIST whose TREE_VALUE is
     603                 :            :      the virtual function this one overrides, and whose TREE_CHAIN is
     604                 :            :      the old DECL_VINDEX.  */
     605                 :            :

     607                 :            :

    2757                 :            :   unsigned unknown_bound_p : 1;            /* var */
    2758                 :            :   unsigned odr_used : 1;                   /* var or fn */
    2759                 :            :   unsigned concept_p : 1;                  /* applies to vars and functions */
    2760                 :            :   unsigned var_declared_inline_p : 1;      /* var */
    2761                 :            :   unsigned dependent_init_p : 1;           /* var */

    2764                 :            :      decls.  */
    2765                 :            :   unsigned module_purview_p : 1;           /* in module purview (not GMF) */
    2766                 :            :   unsigned module_import_p : 1;            /* from an import */
    2767                 :            :   unsigned module_entity_p : 1;            /* is in the entitity ary &
    2768                 :            :                                               hash.  */
    2769                 :            :   /* VAR_DECL or FUNCTION_DECL has attached decls.     */
    2770                 :            :   unsigned module_attached_p : 1;
    2771                 :            : 
    2772                 :            :   /* 12 spare bits.  */
    2773                 :            : };
    2774                 :            : 
    2775                 :            : /* True for DECL codes which have template info and access.  */
    2776                 :            : #define LANG_DECL_HAS_MIN(NODE)                 \
    2777                 :            :   (VAR_OR_FUNCTION_DECL_P (NODE)                \
    2778                 :            :    || TREE_CODE (NODE) == FIELD_DECL            \
    2779                 :            :    || TREE_CODE (NODE) == CONST_DECL            \

    2799                 :            :      In a function-scope TREE_STATIC VAR_DECL or IMPLICIT_TYPEDEF_P TYPE_DECL,
    2800                 :            :      this is DECL_DISCRIMINATOR.

    4946                 :            :      2=partial or explicit specialization, e.g.:
    4947                 :            : 
    4948                 :            :         template <> int min<int> (int, int),
    4949                 :            : 
    4950                 :            :      3=explicit instantiation, e.g.:
    4951                 :            : 
    4952                 :            :         template int min<int> (int, int);
    4953                 :            : 
    4954                 :            :    Note that NODE will be marked as a specialization even if the
    4955                 :            :    template it is instantiating is not a primary template.  For
    4956                 :            :    example, given:
    4957                 :            : 
    4958                 :            :      template <typename T> struct O {
    4959                 :            :        void f();
    4960                 :            :        struct I {};
    4961                 :            :      };
    4962                 :            : 
    4963                 :            :    both O<int>::f and O<int>::I will be marked as instantiations.
    4964                 :            : 
    4965                 :            :    If DECL_USE_TEMPLATE is nonzero, then DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO will also
    4966                 :            :    be non-NULL.  */
    4967                 :            : #define DECL_USE_TEMPLATE(NODE) (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (NODE)->u.base.use_template)
    4968                 :            : 
    4969                 :            : /* Like DECL_USE_TEMPLATE, but for class types.  */
    4970                 :            : #define CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE(NODE) \

    4972                 :            :

    4974                 :            : #define CLASSTYPE_SPECIALIZATION_OF_PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P(NODE)    \
    4975                 :            :   (CLASS_TYPE_P (NODE)                                          \

    4977                 :            :    && PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P (CLASSTYPE_TI_TEMPLATE (NODE)))
    4978                 :            :

    5002                 :            : #define CLASSTYPE_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
    5003                 :            :   (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 3)
    5004                 :            : #define SET_CLASSTYPE_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
    5005                 :            :   (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 3)
    5006                 :            : 
    5007                 :            : /* Nonzero if DECL is a friend function which is an instantiation
    5008                 :            :    from the point of view of the compiler, but not from the point of
    5009                 :            :    view of the language.  For example given:
    5010                 :            :       template <class T> struct S { friend void f(T) {}; };

    5058                 :            : 
    5059                 :            : /* A thunk is a stub function.
    5060                 :            : 
    5061                 :            :    A thunk is an alternate entry point for an ordinary FUNCTION_DECL.
    5062                 :            :    The address of the ordinary FUNCTION_DECL is given by the
    5063                 :            :    DECL_INITIAL, which is always an ADDR_EXPR whose operand is a
    5064                 :            :    FUNCTION_DECL.  The job of the thunk is to either adjust the this
    5065                 :            :    pointer before transferring control to the FUNCTION_DECL, or call
    5066                 :            :    FUNCTION_DECL and then adjust the result value. Note, the result
    5067                 :            :    pointer adjusting thunk must perform a call to the thunked
    5068                 :            :    function, (or be implemented via passing some invisible parameter
    5069                 :            :    to the thunked function, which is modified to perform the
    5070                 :            :    adjustment just before returning).
    5071                 :            : 
    5072                 :            :    A thunk may perform either, or both, of the following operations:
    5073                 :            : 
    5074                 :            :    o Adjust the this or result pointer by a constant offset.
    5075                 :            :    o Adjust the this or result pointer by looking up a vcall or vbase offset
    5076                 :            :      in the vtable.
    5077                 :            : 
    5078                 :            :    A this pointer adjusting thunk converts from a base to a derived
    5079                 :            :    class, and hence adds the offsets. A result pointer adjusting thunk
    5080                 :            :    converts from a derived class to a base, and hence subtracts the
    5081                 :            :    offsets.  If both operations are performed, then the constant
    5082                 :            :    adjustment is performed first for this pointer adjustment and last
    5083                 :            :    for the result pointer adjustment.
    5084                 :            : 
    5085                 :            :    The constant adjustment is given by THUNK_FIXED_OFFSET.  If the
    5086                 :            :    vcall or vbase offset is required, THUNK_VIRTUAL_OFFSET is
    5087                 :            :    used. For this pointer adjusting thunks, it is the vcall offset
    5088                 :            :    into the vtable.  For result pointer adjusting thunks it is the
    5089                 :            :    binfo of the virtual base to convert to.  Use that binfo's vbase
    5090                 :            :    offset.
    5091                 :            : 
    5092                 :            :    It is possible to have equivalent covariant thunks.  These are
    5093                 :            :    distinct virtual covariant thunks whose vbase offsets happen to
    5094                 :            :    have the same value.  THUNK_ALIAS is used to pick one as the
    5095                 :            :    canonical thunk, which will get all the this pointer adjusting
    5096                 :            :    thunks attached to it.  */
    5097                 :            : 
    5098                 :            : /* An integer indicating how many bytes should be subtracted from the
    5099                 :            :    this or result pointer when this function is called.  */
    5100                 :            : #define THUNK_FIXED_OFFSET(DECL) \
    5101                 :            :   (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (THUNK_FUNCTION_CHECK (DECL))->u.fn.u5.fixed_offset)
    5102                 :            : 
    5103                 :            : /* A tree indicating how to perform the virtual adjustment. For a this
    5104                 :            :    adjusting thunk it is the number of bytes to be added to the vtable
    5105                 :            :    to find the vcall offset. For a result adjusting thunk, it is the
    5106                 :            :    binfo of the relevant virtual base.  If NULL, then there is no
    5107                 :            :    virtual adjust.  (The vptr is always located at offset zero from
    5108                 :            :    the this or result pointer.)  (If the covariant type is within the
    5109                 :            :    class hierarchy being laid out, the vbase index is not yet known
    5110                 :            :    at the point we need to create the thunks, hence the need to use
    5111                 :            :    binfos.)  */
    5112                 :            : 
    5113                 :            : #define THUNK_VIRTUAL_OFFSET(DECL) \
    5114                 :            :   (LANG_DECL_MIN_CHECK (FUNCTION_DECL_CHECK (DECL))->access)
    5115                 :            : 
    5116                 :            : /* A thunk which is equivalent to another thunk.  */

    5119                 :            :
